  "query": "What design and placement factors influence the successful use of bat boxes by bats?",
  "relevant_summary": "Several factors related to bat box design and placement have been shown to influence their use by bats.\n\nIn terms of design, black bat boxes were found to be used more than grey, white, or wooden ones (1024). One study indicated that larger bat boxes had higher occupancy rates (1024). The material of the box also matters, with one study finding that resin boxes were occupied more quickly than wooden ones, and another showing higher occupancy in concrete boxes compared to wood (1024). Specific designs like rocket boxes, two-compartment boxes, and those mimicking tree trunks have proven effective, and different bat species may prefer different designs (1024).\n\nPlacement is also critical. The orientation of the box and its exposure to sunlight can affect occupancy (1024). While the effect of height is debated, with some studies showing it matters and others finding no effect, boxes on buildings were found to have higher occupancy than those on trees (1024). The surrounding habitat is a factor, with higher occupancy observed in farm forestry over native forest and in pine stands over mixed deciduous stands (1024). Additionally, higher success rates are seen when boxes are installed in areas where bats were already known to roost, and installing a greater number of boxes across a site increases the likelihood of occupation (1024).\n\nHowever, when creating alternative roosts as part of a development, bat boxes or bat lofts that were built to replace destroyed roosts were four times less likely to be used by returning bats than roosts that were retained during development (949). Two other studies found that bats did not use any of the alternative roosts provided in bat houses or a purpose-built bat wall after being excluded from buildings (949).",
