{
  "query": "How do different types of purpose-built road crossing structures compare in effectiveness for bats?",
  "relevant_summary": "Several studies have evaluated the effectiveness of different road crossing structures for bats, including bat gantries, overpasses, and underpasses (976, 977, 978).\n\nStudies on bat gantries in the UK and France have shown that fewer bats used these structures compared to crossing the road at traffic height (978). In one instance, a bat gantry was not used at all, and in another case, a temporary gantry was used by three bat species or species groups, but almost half of the bats crossed the road at other locations (978).\n\nThe effectiveness of overpasses has been found to vary. In Australia, one study recorded the same number of bat species at an overpass as in the surrounding forest and bushland (977). However, studies in Ireland and France indicated that up to 75% of bats crossed the road at traffic level or other locations, despite the presence of overpasses (977). The design of the overpass appears to be a key factor, as a UK study found that an overpass with planters was used by two-thirds of crossing bats, whereas an unvegetated overpass was completely unused (977).\n\nUnderpasses and culverts are also used by bats for crossing roads, although the proportion of use varies, with some bats still choosing to fly over the road (976). The use of these structures is influenced by their type and height, the width of the road, and the composition of the surrounding landscape, such as the presence of forests and hedgerows (976). Furthermore, bat species adapted to cluttered habitats were observed to use smaller underpasses and culverts more frequently than species adapted to open or edge habitats (976).",
